ndix 3 -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aIn an effort to fight climate change, many cities try to boost their cycling levels. They often look towards the Dutch for guidance. However, historians have only begun to uncover how and why the Netherlands became the premier cycling country of the world. Why were Dutch cyclists so successful in their fight for a place on the road? Cycling Pathways explores the long political struggle that culminated in today's high cycling levels. Delving into the archives, it uncovers the important role of social movements and shows in detail how these interacted with national, provincial, and urban engineers and policymakers to govern the distribution of road space and construction of cycling infrastructure. It discusses a wide range of topics, ranging from activists to engineering committees, from urban commuters to recreational cyclists and from the early 1900s to today in order to uncover the long and all-but-forgotten history of Dutch cycling governance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0https://www.aup.nl/en/publish/open-access  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aBicycle laneszNetherlands. 0aCyclingzNetherlandsxHistory. 4a20th century, c 1900 to c 1999. 4aContemporary History. 4aDutch and The Netherlands. 4aHistory of engineering and technology. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aNetherlands. 4aPolitics and Government. 4aSocial and cultural history. 4aSociology and Social History. 4aUrban and municipal planning and policy. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Western.2bisacsh  aCycling, History, the Netherlands, Governance, Social Movements.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruyt